@labrys I think that that last one is acceptable for now. `tzlocal()` is a wrapper around the `time` functions related to time zone, while `tzwinlocal()` is pulling its information from the Windows registry keys.

I think the concept of "equality" of time zone objects is a bit fuzzy. While the two things do represent the same time zone, one may be richer than the other and I think it's worth giving careful thought as to how the two might diverge (maybe the answer is 'not at all', but I dunno).

I'd rather err on the side of having the two compare not equal because I feel like that is less likely to create lasting API implications (e.g. people won't rely on two things comparing equal if they represent the same value even if they are of different types).

