@Swanson-Hysell The workflow for recent Santa Cruz paleomag is to create a large file with the magnetometer control software with data for each stratigraphic section (the "location" in MagIC parlance) in one large .scz file. We should be able to extract all the information to fill out the location, site, sample, specimen, and measurement data from this xml file. The interpretations for each sample is saved in a .pmm file, one for each lava flow (site). Then another .pmm file is used to determine location level interpretations. We also have .pmd files for analyzing measurement data in the Enkin program, but we don't need those if the .scz is not corrupted or lost. For uploading past studies, I think that running a script on the command line to put together the information in the .scz file withe a multiple of .pmm files would be great. Going into the future I imagine importing the .scz file into pmag_gui for people to do their interpretations. Pmag_gui is better than the old enkin program we used, is an active project, and is being improved. 

@Caoimhinmg @moonshoes87 I have some time to work on writing the Santa Cruz converter before I go down there on the 8th. Having the ability to make quick changes to the code as issues arise on-site is crucial to success. I want to have it in the native 3.0 data model, but many functions would have to be re-written such as pmag.magic_write. Should functions be added with similar names like magic_write3 or are there problems with the old workflow that could be addressed at this time?

I'll add a directory for .scz data files and put some associated .pmm in there as well. Pete Lippert's lab may also be able to use this converter program to get in measurement data.

